observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Management agreed that the City Mayor:

Temporarily relieve the members of the Inventory Committee from all of their regular duties to devote their full time in the completion of the physical inventory taking, preparation of RPCPPE and reconciliation of the report with the GSO and Accounting Records;

Require the GSO to submit immediately the RPCPPE as of December 31, 2022 together with the Inventory Count Sheet/s.

We recommended that the City Mayor:

Require the City Treasurer’s Office to:

Avail remedies for collections of delinquent RPT and SET by administrative action through a levy on real property or by judicial action;

We recommended, and Management agreed, that the City Mayor (CITY MAYOR):

Require all revenue collectors/AOs to turn over the full amount of their collections intact at the close of business day to the LO;



Require the LO to strictly verify the RCDs of AOs;

We recommended that the City Mayor (CITY MAYOR) direct the:

City Accountant to coordinate with the CGSO and offices concerned to reconcile the inventory account balance and to prepare adjusting entries;

Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of inventories on a semester basis, reconcile the result of physical count with the property and the accounting records, and prepare and submit a copy of the RPCI to the Audit Team within the reglementary period, pursuant to the pertinent provision of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs Volume I

We recommended that the LCE direct:
The CAO to prepare a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to derecognize in the books of accounts the ten (10) LGSF-SBDP funded projects, totaling ₱79,011,995.59 turned-over to barangays;
The CAO to prepare a JEV to transfer the three (3) LGU-funded projects, totaling ₱6,440,017.22 from PPE account to Donations account, and derecognized the related depreciation expense and accumulated depreciation accounts;
The GSO to exclude the turned-over and donated PPEs from the RPCPPE and provide the CAO with copies of pertinent documents; and
The GSO to ensure the proper documentation of PPEs transferred to other government agencies or local government units and submit copies to the CAO for JEV preparation to derecognize transferred PPEs.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:
City Offices with PCF to establish fund to an amount that is only sufficient for one month;
Petty Cash Custodian (PCC) to ensure the preparation of PCV for every PCF disbursement and an Inspection and Acceptance Report for every purchase;
PCC to require the submission of pre and post repair Inspection Report with pictures before, during and after for liquidation of cash disbursed for repairs;
PCC to refrain disbursing PCF for reimbursement of expenses; and
City Department Heads/Supervisors to refrain from approving reimbursement charges to PCF.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:
General Services Office to conduct a comprehensive inventory of all insurable properties and equipment and identify assets lacking insurance coverage;
GSO to prepare and submit the PIF to the Office of the Auditor not later than April 30 of each year;
GSO to collaborate with the GSIS to promptly insure all identified properties equipment under the GSIS General Insurance Fund;
City Budget Office to ensure that sufficient funds is allocated in the annual budget to cover insurance premiums, ensuring financial resources are available for timely payments;
Internal Audit System Office to schedule periodic audits to assess compliance with insurance requirements and address any discrepancies promptly

We recommended, and Management agreed, that the City Mayor (CITY MAYOR):

Require all revenue collectors/AOs to turn over the full amount of their collections intact at the close of business day to the LO;

Require the LO to strictly verify the RCDs of AOs; and

We recommended that the City Mayor (CITY MAYOR) direct the: 

City Accountant to coordinate with the CGSO and offices concerned to reconcile the inventory account balance and to prepare adjusting entries;


Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of inventories on a semester basis, reconcile the result of physical count with the property and the accounting records, and prepare and submit a copy of the RPCI to the Audit Team within the reglementary period, pursuant to the pertinent provisions of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume I.

We recommended that the management:
Stop the practice of procuring of goods and services thru cash advances for the implementation of programs and activities.
Submit valid justification for the procurement of regular items through cash advance;
Require the SDOs of the CAs totaling to ₱4,139,780.00 to liquidate immediately their past due accounts;
Require all SDOs to return immediately any excess/ unutilized cash advance upon completion of the purpose of the special undertakings; and
Require the City Accountant to:
send demand letters to SDOs with past due CAs;
sign “received” with date the reports of disbursements and record the liquidation of each cash advances within 10 days after the receipt of the report and supporting documents from the AO; and
cause the withholding of the SDO’s salary when no liquidation of the previous cash advance is received on or before January 20.

We recommended that the management:
Require the City Accountant, the City Treasurer and the PPAs’ Focal Persons to review the financial records, statements, and prior years’ transactions in order to track the history and origin of the dormant fund transfers totaling ₱4,582,943.73;
Require the City Accountant to conduct confirmation of the balance of unliquidated fund transfers from source NGAs that granted assistance to LGUs in order to reconcile the balances of fund transfers;
Require the City Accountant and the City Treasurer to immediately return the balances of fund transfers for completed PPAs totaling ₱2,182,660.60; and
Assess and review the necessity and feasibility of the PPAs funded by NGAs through fund transfer; otherwise, return the funds to the source agencies.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the City Human Resource Management Officer to: 

a.	Prepare the Organizational Structure and Staffing Pattern Plan in order to assess the required number of JO workers to be hired based on necessity and financial capability of the City;

b.	Submit the lacking 144 Job Order Contracts to the Audit Team;

c.	Fill up all vacant positions under Plantilla to minimize the number of JO workers to be hired; and

d.	Ensure that Job Order contracts or Contracts of Service are duly signed by the JO workers and contain their duties and responsibilities, compensation payment on a daily basis, specific place of assignment especially those assigned in field work; and a copy submitted to the HRMO;

We likewise recommended that the Management require the City Internal Audit System Office to monitor compliance of the audit recommendations by the concerned employees

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) direct the:
1)City Accountant to coordinate with the CGSO and offices concerned to reconcile the inventory account balance and to prepare adjusting entries;
2)CGSO and the officials concerned in the Supply Unit to comply with the provisions of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs on recording of receipt and issuance of inventories, the maintenance of stock cards, and the use of issued RIS for issuances and preparation of monthly RSMIs based on RISs and the submission of copies thereof to the City Accountant for recording;
3)City Accountant to prepare and maintain SLCs for Inventories Held for Distribution and other inventory items; and
4)Inventory Committee to conduct physical inventory in Not Still, physical count conducted as of year-end.

